<section id="howto">
<div class="page-header">
    <h1>How to use LiftApp <small> What the site does and how you can use it</small></h1>
</div>
<div class="row">
	<div class="span8">
	<h2>What is a 5x5 workout? <small>It's a weight lifting routine that has you do 5 sets with 5 reps of compound muscle exercises.</small></h2>
	</div> 
	<br/>

    <div class="span4">
      <h2>1. Check Out Exercises</h2>
      <p>LiftApp has a big list of exercises. Check it out. If you don't see the exercises you want, create them.</p>
      <p>When you add an exercise to the database every user can now see them and use them in their workouts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="span4">
      <h2>2. Create a Group</h2>
      <p>I know what you're thinking! It's time to make a 5x5 out of my exercises. Groups of workouts let your organize your workouts. A common set of workouts in a groups is Day 1, Day 2, Day 3. So create a group first then add workouts to it.</p>

    </div>
  </div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="span4">
      <h2>3. Create a Workout</h2>
      <p>When you create a workout you select a group for it to belong to. No 5x5 workout should be done every day, you want to switch it up, so we have groups! Then you give your workout a name. Then you add your exercises.</p>
      <p>Once you create a workout every user can user can do it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="span4">
      <h2>4. Do a Workout</h2>
      <p>When you see the workout list, click the name of the workout you want to do. Look for the <%= link_to "Do it!", "#howto", :class => "btn btn-primary"  %> button. </p>
      <p> When you are entering your workout weight, be sure to do five sets at that weight. Some folks vary the weight over five sets and take the average.
	
    </div>
  </div>

</section>


